Subject: [PATCH 50/87] incr-check: Kill child process on error
X-Developer-Signature: v=1; a=openpgp-sha256; l=1588; i=xtexchooser@duck.com;
 h=from:subject; bh=1xG7ThpMUTkcckjHjmw4p/eM5dpPUC07T5Pd20e7VqE=;
 b=owGbwMvMwCW2U4Ij7wZL9ETG02pJDJkmdvazdhdcXWhsl3tk9eykI6xvvxXvZH+jpnXkksKyw
 Gl2psmSHaUsDGJcDLJiiixFhg3erDrp/KLLymVh5rAygQxh4OIUgIl8WMXw3/PWj+fHziQeSZ8o
 ef2DTonLTe3EJtnyHXbHX3DyrQj494yR4eX118l66XvOpWgdas5fnfFBKmhjw+/a9i2LNYubVCo
 K2QE=
X-Developer-Key: i=xtexchooser@duck.com; a=openpgp;
 fpr=7231804B052C670F15A6771DB918086ED8045B91

Since the child process is spawned with the tmp directory as its CWD, the child process opens it without DELETE access. On error, the child process would still be alive while the tmp directory is attempting to be deleted, so it would fail with `.SHARING_VIOLATION => return error.FileBusy`.

Fixes arguably the least important part of #22510, since it's only the directory itself that would fail to get deleted, all the files inside would get deleted just fine.

(cherry picked from commit 5358af7ba4cf16bef1734729646b99842e439916)
---
 tools/incr-check.zig | 5 +++++
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+)

diff --git a/tools/incr-check.zig b/tools/incr-check.zig
index c187c84ae51e..90958df44c3d 100644
--- a/tools/incr-check.zig
+++ b/tools/incr-check.zig
@@ -185,6 +185,9 @@ pub fn main() !void {
         };
 
         try child.spawn();
+        errdefer {
+            _ = child.kill() catch {};
+        }
 
         var poller = std.Io.poll(arena, Eval.StreamEnum, .{
             .stdout = child.stdout.?,
@@ -591,6 +594,8 @@ const Eval = struct {
     fn fatal(eval: *Eval, comptime fmt: []const u8, args: anytype) noreturn {
         eval.tmp_dir.close();
         if (!eval.preserve_tmp_on_fatal) {
+            // Kill the child since it holds an open handle to its CWD which is the tmp dir path
+            _ = eval.child.kill() catch {};
             std.fs.cwd().deleteTree(eval.tmp_dir_path) catch |err| {
                 std.log.warn("failed to delete tree '{s}': {s}", .{ eval.tmp_dir_path, @errorName(err) });
             };
